Use the bucket that fits the submitted country. The tail buckets are intentional: broad Mexico, Panama/Costa Rica, Colombia/Peru, Argentina/Chile, and Brazil examples do not substitute for the less obvious country pools.

Evidence roles:
- `implementation_actor_role`: deployment-specific evidence naming at least one implementation actor and its concrete role, such as validator or fare-equipment supplier, back-office integrator, payment acquirer, processor, concessionaire, bank, transport-payment platform, card-network transit certification/program participant, app/QR platform, system integrator, or other implementation counterparty. Accepted card brands, payment logos, generic vendor capability pages, broad regional thought leadership, and operator pages that merely show riders can pay do not count unless they name a deployment-specific actor and role.
- `contract_or_regulatory_instrument`: procurement, concession, public contract, regulatory authorization, public implementation instrument, certification instrument, acceptance or testing milestone, formal award, tender document, public contract register, authority implementation note, or comparable instrument that structures or authorizes the submitted deployment phase. It must name the instrument or authority action and connect it to a concrete implementation mechanism; a public launch announcement, rider FAQ, app download page, vendor product page, or line-expansion summary does not count by itself. Broad authority news that merely says a payment mode launched is not enough.
- `technical_payment_integration_detail`: deployment-specific technical or payment-industry implementation detail, such as named validator hardware/software integration, back-office fare collection modules, EMV/open-loop certification, fare-media tokenization, QR/Pix/NFC integration architecture, processor/acquirer routing, settlement or clearing arrangement, fare-card personalization, account-based fare architecture, benefit/gratuity handling, equipment acceptance, or comparable system detail. Generic "tap to pay" text, accepted-card/logo lists, recharge-machine mentions, broad platform descriptions, and rider how-to pages do not count unless they expose deployment-specific implementation detail beyond rider availability.

Role-specific source posture:
- `implementation_actor_role` should normally come from a named implementation participant, supplier, acquirer, processor, bank, network, validator/back-office provider, app/QR platform, concessionaire, certifier, systems integrator, or a formal implementation artifact that states a concrete actor role for the submitted deployment.
- `contract_or_regulatory_instrument` should normally come from a formal or primary implementation artifact: procurement/contract portal, concession record, regulator, certifier, public implementation register, authority/operator technical appendix, tender, award, acceptance/testing milestone, or comparable public instrument source.
- `technical_payment_integration_detail` can come from either a formal technical/implementation artifact or a counterparty/industry technical source, but it must expose deployment-specific payment, validator, back-office, tokenization, certification, routing, settlement, clearing, equipment-acceptance, or integration detail.

Ordinary rider-facing pages, accepted-card pages, generic product pages, generic vendor thought leadership, and broad launch summaries do not become valid just because they mention the payment mode. A page may support more than one evidence role only when it still exposes the role-specific implementation anchor for each submitted record.

Public transit fare-payment systems can include open-loop/contactless EMV, account-based fare collection, QR/Pix/app payment, closed-loop smart cards, mobile-wallet transit acceptance, validators, back offices, electronic ticketing, and transport-benefit or gratuity/concession fare handling.

Public deployment status and rider fare access must still be clear for every source, but they are not separate evidence roles. Ordinary online top-up pages count only when tied to rider payment, validation, boarding, gates, validators, or fare access for a named public transport deployment and when they also carry the submitted implementation role. Broad fare brands are not enough; the deployment scope should be a specific line group, modal rollout, city/region activation, gratuity transition, open-loop phase, QR rollout, validator refresh, procurement-backed implementation, or named operator/supplier phase. Parking, tolling, retail-only payments, generic smart-city payments, private shuttle payments, generic market reports, broad regional card-network thought leadership, and pure future plans with no public pilot, rollout, transition, or operating evidence do not count.

Requirements:
- The page must tie the claimed country, city_or_region, system_or_operator, program_name, and deployment_scope to the same named public transit fare-payment deployment or implementation phase.
- The page must show that the deployment concerns rider fare payment, fare validation, boarding or gate access, validators, electronic ticketing, fare collection back office, benefit/gratuity/concession fare handling, or a comparable public-transport fare-access mechanism.
- The page must supply the implementation anchor requested by `evidence_type`, with source posture appropriate to that role: a named deployment-specific actor with its concrete role for `implementation_actor_role`, a named formal contract/procurement/concession/regulatory/certification/acceptance-testing/public implementation instrument for `contract_or_regulatory_instrument`, or deployment-specific technical/payment/validator/back-office/tokenization/settlement/clearing integration detail for `technical_payment_integration_detail`.
